00020 =head1 NAME
00021 
00022 WeBWorK::DB::Schema::NewSQL::VersionedMerge - hack to get merged records

00060 sub get_fields_where {
00061     my ( $self, $fields, $where, $order ) = @_;
00062 
00063     # note: this is ugly because we've got two different table models 
00064         #   that we're combining: {}_user and {}_version.  $self is inheriting
00065     #   from Merge.pm, and so is using the first model; thus it doesn't
00066         #   know how to deal with where clauses that include version_ids, 
00067         #   and calling $self->conv_where() will therefore bail when we have
00068         #   a restriction on the version_id.  if we use 
00069     #   $db->{*_version}->conv_where(), there's no error, and the set_id
00070     #   gets converted to the form we need to find the record in the 
00071     #   *_user table.
00072         # however, to make things more interesting, if we're entering here 
00073         #   from a call of $db->{set_version_merged}->gets(), there's no 
00074     #   trouble, because we're using $self->keyparts_to_where(), which 
00075     #   has no trouble returning a %$where hash including a version_id key.
00076     # the result is that we have to check for what $where is saying
00077     #   here, even though we'd like to suppress that for the different
00078     #   _get_fields_where_prepex() routines, because we have to be sure 
00079     #   that we don't hand a @$where clause including version_id 
00080     #   information to $self->conv_where().  yuck!
00081 
00082     if ( ref($where) eq 'ARRAY' ) {
00083         my ( $nvtable ) = ( $self->table =~ /(.+)_merged/ );
00084         my $newWhere = $self->{db}->{$nvtable}->conv_where( $where );
00085         if ( defined( $newWhere->{set_id} ) && 
00086          $newWhere->{set_id} =~ /,v(\d+)$/ ) {
00087         $newWhere->{version_id} = $1;
00088         $newWhere->{set_id} =~ s/,v(\d+)$//; 
00089         }
00090         $where = $newWhere;
00091     }
00092 
00093     # get merged {}_user and {} records; to do this we have to be 
00094     # careful that we don't get fooled by references to versions
00095     my %nvWhere = %$where;
00096     for my $key ( keys %nvWhere ) {
00097         delete( $nvWhere{$key} ) if $key eq 'version_id';
00098     }
00099     my @nvFields = grep { $_ ne 'version_id' } @$fields;
00100 
00101     my $sth = $self->_get_fields_where_prepex(\@nvFields, \%nvWhere, $order);
00102     my @results = @{ $sth->fetchall_arrayref };
00103     $sth->finish;
00104 
00105     # then get data for this version
00106     $sth = $self->_get_fields_where_prepex_extra( $fields, $where, $order );
00107     my @vresults = @{ $sth->fetchall_arrayref };
00108     $sth->finish;
00109 
00110     # build a set of results hashes to facilitate merging the two sets
00111     # of data, which will have different fields
00112     my @res = ();
00113     foreach my $r ( @results ) {
00114         push(@res, { map {$nvFields[$_]=>$r->[$_]} (0..$#nvFields) });
00115     }
00116     my @vres = ();
00117     foreach my $r ( @vresults ) {
00118         push(@vres, {map {$fields->[$_]=>$r->[$_]} (0..$#{@$fields})});
00119     }
00120 
00121 #   my $rstr = "( ";
00122 #   foreach (@results) { $rstr .= "[" . join(',', @{$_}) . "]\n"; }
00123 #   warn("$rstr )\n");
00124 #   my $vstr = "( ";
00125 #   foreach (@vresults) { $vstr .= "[" . join(',', @{$_}) . "]\n"; }
00126 #   warn("$vstr )\n");
00127 
00128     # finally, brutally merge these
00129     my @mergedResults = ();
00130     for ( my $i=0; $i<@vres; $i++ ) {
00131         my @mres = ();
00132         foreach my $f ( @$fields ) {
00133             # there should be a more elegant way of doing this
00134             if ( defined( $vres[$i]->{$f} ) ) {
00135                 push( @mres, $vres[$i]->{$f} );
00136             } elsif ( defined( $res[$i]->{$f} ) ) {
00137                 push( @mres, $res[$i]->{$f} );
00138             } else {
00139                 push( @mres, undef );
00140             }
00141         }
00142         push( @mergedResults, [ @mres ] );
00143     }
00144 
00145 #   $rstr = "( ";
00146 #   foreach (@mergedResults) { $rstr .= "[" . join(',', @{$_}) . "]\n"; }
00147 #   warn("$rstr )\n");
00148 
00149     return @mergedResults;
00150 }
00151 
00152 sub _get_fields_where_prepex_extra { 
00153     my ( $self, $fields, $where, $order ) = @_;
00154 
00155     # we have a problem with the $where parameters, because they 
00156     # haven't been sent through the Versioned where clause generators
00157     # manually fix those to deal with the set_id and version_id keys
00158     my %vWhere = %$where;
00159     if ( defined($vWhere{'set_id'}) && defined($vWhere{'version_id'}) ) {
00160         $vWhere{'set_id'} = make_vsetID($vWhere{'set_id'}, $vWhere{'version_id'});
00161         delete( $vWhere{'version_id'} );
00162     } elsif ( defined($vWhere{'set_id'}) || defined($vWhere{'version_id'}) ) {
00163         if ( defined($vWhere{'version_id'}) ) {
00164             warn("Error: where clause includes version_id and not a set_id.\n");
00165             delete( $vWhere{'version_id'} );
00166         }
00167         if ( defined($vWhere{'set_id'}) ) {
00168             warn("Error: where clause includes set_id and not a version_id ($vWhere{set_id}).\n");
00169             delete( $vWhere{'set_id'} );
00170         }
00171     }
00172 #   warn("fields = ", "@$fields", "\n");
00173 #   warn("vWhere = ", join("; ", map{"$_=>$vWhere{$_}"} keys %vWhere), "\n");
00174 
00175     my $db = $self->{db};
00176 
00177     my ($table) = ($self->table =~ /(.+)_merged/);
00178     return $db->{$table}->_get_fields_where_prepex( $fields, \%vWhere, $order );
00179 }
